snippet.textDisplay: My primary concern here is the supposition of future crime in both the articles and the closing arguments.  He talks as if the investigations into the Bidens happened, which it did not.  Most of this case is based on what could happen, not what did happen.  What did happen was asking for the investigation.  Everything else, including the harm against Joe, is presumed to result some time in the future.  I'm not a fan of future crime.  If we're going to impeach, let's stick with what actually happened.  Examples: Johnson really did fire his secretary of war.  Nixon really did raid his campaign fund to pay criminals who were later convicted (but prior to impeachment).  Bill Clinton really did commit perjury.  Trump really did ask Zolensky to investigate the Bidens.  That is the only thing here that can be scrutinized as potential high crimes and misdemeanors.  The rest is policy debate and presumption of future outcome, with some intent thrown in.
